The defendant Charles McLain was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Receiving or Concealing Stolen Property (<=$2500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.34(1)(a).
  • Take/Drive Veh. w/o Consent-Abandon Veh., a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.23(3m).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Charles McLain in court with attorney Vincent Paul Guimont.  Tyrone Martin St. Junior appeared for the State of Wisconsin. 

Sentencing proceeded.    Statements made by counsel and defendant.  

AS TO COUNT 1:
The Court sentenced the defendant to serve 6 months in the House of Correction, concurrent to any other sentence, with credit for 2 days time served, Huber privileges for work, school, and treatment.  

AS TO COUNT 2:
The Court sentenced the defendant to serve  6 months in the House of Correction, concurrent to any other sentence, with credit for 2 days time served, Huber privileges for work, school, and treatment.  

AS TO EACH COUNT:
The court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for a period of 18 months with the following conditions:

*Mental health assessment and comply with any treatment deemed necessary by the department.
*Alcohol and drug assessment and comply with any treatment deemed necessary by the department.
*Absolute sobriety.
*Random urine screens.  No positive results.
*No illegal drugs.
*No controlled substances without valid prescription.
*No contact with drug community.
*No contact with the victim: Nicole D.
*Seek and maintain full time employment when not enrolled in school.
*Obtain high school diploma or GED.
*Cognitive Behavior Therapy.

Restitution is ordered in the amount of $405.26 to be paid to Nicole D.

- The Court ordered no DNA sample or DNA surcharge, as this case predates the change in law.
- Pay all costs, fees, restitution and surcharges, by DOC out of up to 25% of any applicable prison funds. To be paid by the end of probation.  If not paid, a civil judgment to be entered.

Appeal rights given.  Court finds the defendant was under the age of 25 at the time of the offense, the charge is a Class H/I felony or misdemeanor, society would not be harmed and the defendant would benefit by expungement.  Upon successful completion of the sentence, defendant may apply for expungement.
